    <stitle>International&#174; MaxxForce&#8482; 5 Engine Service Manual - Power Cylinder - Cleaning, Inspection, and
        Measurement - Pistons
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="s26507.2.2" svcproctype="inspect" graphiccount="4">
        <title>Pistons</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect pistons for scuffed or scored skirts, cracked or worn ring lands, and cracked or
                scuffed pin bores. Replace any pistons showing such damage.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="e300810" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd04/d0420.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Top compression ring groove measurement</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Piston gauge pins (0.082 in)</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check top compression ring groove for wear as follows:</para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Top compression ring groove is a keystone design which requires measurement over gauge pins to
                        determine ring groove wear.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Install the Piston Gauge Pins (0.082 in) in the top ring groove. Piston gauge pins must
                    be parallel. See
                    <hotlnk document="eges390_327.xml" xrefid="E3008C">Special Service Tools
                        <xref refid="E3008C"/>
                    </hotlnk>
                    .
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Use a 3 - 4 inch outside micrometer to measure diameter over piston gauge pins. See
                    <hotlnk document="eges390_325.xml" xrefid="E3008A">Specifications
                        <xref refid="E3008A"/>
                    </hotlnk>
                    .
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">If measurement over the gauge pin is not within specifications, excessive piston groove
                    wear exists. Replace piston.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <figure id="e300811" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd04/d0403.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Ring groove clearance measurement (intermediate ring shown)</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Compression ring groove</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Intermediate compression ring groove</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Feeler gauge</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check side clearance of intermediate ring groove as follows:</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Place outer edge of new ring in its respective ring groove.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Roll ring entirely around piston in its respective groove. Make sure ring is able to
                    move freely in its groove.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Use a
                    <hotlnk document="eges390_327.xml" xrefid="E3008C">feeler gauge
                        <xref refid="E3008C"/>
                    </hotlnk>
                    to check side clearance. Excessive side clearance indicates ring groove wear and requires piston
                    replacement. See
                    <hotlnk document="eges390_325.xml" xrefid="E3008A">Specifications
                        <xref refid="E3008A"/>
                    </hotlnk>
                    .
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check side clearance of oil control ring groove as follows:</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Place outer edge of new ring in oil control ring groove.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Roll ring entirely around piston in its respective groove. Make sure ring is able to
                    move freely in groove.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Use a feeler gauge to check side clearance of oil control ring in its respective groove.
                    Excessive side clearance indicates ring groove wear and requires piston replacement. See
                    <hotlnk document="eges390_325.xml" xrefid="E3008A">Specifications
                        <xref refid="E3008A"/>
                    </hotlnk>
                    .
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <figure id="e300812" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd04/d0416.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Piston skirt diameter measurement</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Piston skirt</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">3-4 inch micrometer</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Measure piston skirt diameter under conditions indicated in the
                <hotlnk document="eges390_325.xml" xrefid="t390001301">Specifications</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="t390001301"/>.
            </para>
            <para>When considering piston replacement, check each
                <hotlnk document="eges390_337.xml" xrefid="s1408.1">cylinder condition and bore out-of-round</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="s1408.1"/>. Cylinder boring may be required. Such bore reconditioning will require oversize
                service pistons.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>In addition to the standard size service piston, the following oversize pistons are available.
                </para>
                <randlist type="bullet">
                    <item>
                        <para>0.254 mm (0.010 in)</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>0.508 mm (0.020 in)</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>0.762 mm (0.030 in)</para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If cylinder walls have minor surface damage but are otherwise within specification (out of
                round), it may be possible to remove such damage by honing.
            </para>
            <para>If cylinder bore is suitable for use without reconditioning, de-glaze bore using a glaze breaker
                brush, then reassemble. See Crankcase and Crankshaft section for the correct de-glazing procedure.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="e300813" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figJ04/J04006.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Piston skirt clearance in cylinder bore</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Piston</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Crankcase</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Feeler gauge</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check
                <hotlnk document="eges390_325.xml" xrefid="t390001301">piston skirt clearance</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="t390001301"/>
                with a feeler gauge in the cylinder bore. Correct as required.
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
